photo.title: you knew just how to awaken me | san francisco

description._content: More of my Golden Gate Bridge photos here; San Francisco photos here. ____________________________________________________ New Year's Day 2013. I got myself out of bed earlier than my being appreciates, but I had also had a quiet New Year's Eve so at least I wasn't contending with any libation-induced sluggishness :) I guess that's a side benefit of not being big into New Year's Eve in general. The drive to the Marin Headlands is about an hour during the wee hours of the morning when there's no traffic. I was there and set up by 5:30am, including the short hike down to the spot from which I shot this. This is similar to another image that I took, but I was zoomed way out for this one compared with the other one. They're both good in my opinion, but this one is easily one of my all-time favorites. I did the fusion of the exposures in Photoshop CS6, so the result was a 32-bit HDR file. There is an incredible amount of data in a 32-bit file. Just as an example, the TIFF of this is 450MB. With all that data there's a lot you can do to bring back details in shadowy areas, for example, but I didn't really do too much of that. In particular, I wanted to keep the hill on the left as a silhouette. I did, however, do a bit of spot shadow recovery on the bridge span. Mostly, I like that the 32-bit method yields a less noisy, more natural-looking exposure-fused image. There are some scenes that I still prefer to tonemap in Photomatix, and I may also try the never-before-used-by-me Exposure Fusion feature in Photomatix to compare it with the Photoshop CS6 method. Should be interesting, but that's not a project I have time for right now.... Why? Well, two weeks from today I'll be arriving in Queenstown, New Zealand to attend a photography workshop. I'm beyond excited, but also a bit stressed about all the things I have to do to get ready for the trip. Time to start making more lists :) _________________________ Thank you for your visits and comments. Please feel free to add notes to any of my images. I do a lot of HDR processing. photo.title: Tribute to the Giants

description._content: World Series Game 4: while the Giants were battling the Tigers, Alan and I decided to shoot the SF skyline bathed in orange. In particular, we wanted to focus on the rare orange beacon atop of the Transamerica Pyramid and embarked on a journey for an up close and personal view. Getting to this spot was rather pricey and tricky. Once again Alan disobeyed his mom and decided to fork over his right kidney, left lung, and eye lashes to pay the price of entry. Once to the top, the view was unbelievable. All clear with some high thin clouds floating above the skyline. However, minutes later the marine fog began creeping into the bay. Slow at first and then faster and faster. Soon enough it appeared to be skunk city as half of the skyline including Coit Tower were engulfed in fog. Much to our luck the fog disappeared almost as fast as it appeared. Shortly after sunset the fog retreated so fast it was completely gone within 15 minutes. Blue hour was in full effect and the city glowed orange. Was it worth it? Only the ninja can answer that. Go Giants! Canon 5D Mark II EF 24-70mm f/2.8L II Website | Facebook | Google+

photo.title: Fireworks and Bay Bridge

description._content: About a month ago, I learned that there would be a fireworks show after the Giants game last week on Friday, and I circled that date in my calendar. As the evening approached, I realized that the fog was most likely going to scuttle my plans. I didn’t want to give up on the shot, so I headed over to Treasure Island to await the end of the game (which seemed to drag on for longer than expected). Shortly before 10pm, the lights in the stadium turned off, and the fireworks show began. Once the fireworks began shooting off into the night sky, I realized that they were much smaller than I had anticipated. I was also situated just a little too far from the ball park to make the fireworks the center of attention. As I cleared my lens of drizzle, I decided to go for a wide angle photo of the Bay Bridge with some small fireworks in the background. I am quite pleased with the results. I like the steely grey colors that came out in the fog. When compared to a similar photo I took on June 1st, the mood is almost a polar opposite. I hope you enjoy. View my website: www.danielpivnick.com

photo.title: The Lineup

description._content: This is a photo that I have been wanting to take for some time now. It needs the right conditions to stand out, which means that the beacon on top of the Transamerica Pyramid needs to be lit. This typically only occurs during the Holidays, so the best time of year to compose this photo is December. I was up on Hawk Hill the night before the big fireworks display scouting it out, and decided that I would go find the correct spot to line up the Pyramid between the Bridge tower. I found my spot, and waited for it to get dark. I was in luck! Not only did the Transamerica beacon happen to be turned on, but Coit Tower was bathed in International Orange to celebrate the Golden Gate Bridge’s 75th Anniversary. I took several photos at different focal lengths and decided that this one was my favorite. A little later in the evening, the Bridge was lit up by spotlights for about 15 minutes in what would turn out to be a test run for the following night. You can see a couple of those images by clicking on my photostream. View my website: www.danielpivnick.com

description._content: One of the best-known groups of "Painted Ladies" is the row of Victorian houses at 710–720 Steiner Street, across from Alamo Square park, in San Francisco. It is sometimes known as "Postcard Row." The houses were built between 1892 and 1896 by developer Matthew Kavanaugh, who lived next door in the 1892 mansion at 722 Steiner Street. This block appears very frequently in media and mass-market photographs of the city and its tourist attractions and have appeared in an estimated 70 movies, TV programs, and ads, including in the opening credits of the television series Full House. photo.title: Transamerica Pyramid

description._content: View On Black The Transamerica Pyramid is the tallest skyscraper in the San Francisco skyline and one of its most iconic. Although the building no longer houses the headquarters of the Transamerica Corporation, it is still strongly associated with the company and is depicted in the company's logo. Designed by architect William Pereira and built by Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction Company, at 260 m (850 ft), upon completion in 1972 it was among the five tallest buildings in the world. The tower has no public access except for the first floor lobby, thus visitors cannot ascend to the top for a panoramic view.

photo.title: Happy New Year!

description._content: Happy New Years to everyone, from San Francisco! My uncle and I reached Treasure Island 7 hours before the fireworks. We sat around adjusting stuff on our cameras for maybe an hour or so, then we just played UNO. I later got bored of that, so we took the public buses to downtown to walk around and get Starbucks. It was a great experience to sit around the freezing Treasure Island with family and look at the skyline of San Francisco. Have a Merry 2013!!

description._content: The first time I shot this, I shot it with film and that film was ruined.  So this time I came back with digital camera.  Didn't use a tripod because last time I took my time to get the framing right, some people came over to ask me what I was doing (he probably thought I was a terrorist).  This is my best try with handheld.  My vision is to make it looks exactly like a pyramid, which this building is taking the cue from.  Picked this side because of the lighting.

photo.title: Transamerica, finallement!

description._content: The Transamerica Pyramid is the most distinctive building in the San Francisco skyline. Despite having been forced to an involuntary scouting of the area, I was still uncomfortable with the composition for this picture. I would have preferred a vertical shot, but the parked cars were in the way. I tried a few different angles and in the end, still had to resort to creative cropping. It would also have been nice to get a light streak up the hill, but I'm more than happy with just the funky street lighting. The time window to get a good exposure was pretty slim. The city lights were strong enough to reflect on the atmospheric humidity as soon as the sky darkened a bit more, destroying the color balance. If anyone wants to get good clear skies in San Francisco, I was told by a couple who passed by that it happens more often in the winter. Like I said, aggressive 4/3 crop. I had to fix two small lens flares as well, I think I did a good job there.

photo.title: Where's Waldo?

description._content: How many people can you spot in this picture? I see at least 32... Was originally planning to head further up the hill for a different sunset shot, but had to turn around after seeing the destination was already engulfed in fog. Here is a quick snapshot before heading back to the car. Still dabbling with the darkside. Its a crappy shot, but posted gargantuan size for those curious how much detail you can capture handheld. Shot with 50/1.8 @ f/8, 1/60s ISO100. Processed in Capture NX2 with WB and mild shadow recovery. Would probably have been a bit sharper on the tripod with MLU. Best viewed large on black...
